					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">One of the commonly cited problems with switching to GNU/Linux is the fact that a lot of the paid-for hardware already in your PC might not be on a distribution's hardware compatibility list. You'll have to pay to replace those, which can prove difficult if you are still in school or if the job market in your area is in the toilet.
<br />
<br />Yes, there exist <a href="http://dosbox.sourceforge.net/news.php?show_news=1" class="postlink">emulators that can run DOS apps</a>, an <a href="http://www.winehq.org/" class="postlink">"emulator" that can run Windows apps</a>, and even <a href="http://www.vmware.com/" class="postlink">emulators that can emulate a whole PC</a>. The CC65 toolchain runs natively under Linux, and some of the Windows-based NES emulators run inside Wine.</div>

